issue_body:
When using FormData with ky and retrying a request inside an afterResponse hook, the Content-Type header boundary becomes mismatched with the actual request body boundary.

Reproduction: Create a ky instance with an afterResponse hook that retries on 401 responses by calling ky(request, options). When the original request uses FormData as the body, the retry request inherits the Content-Type header from the original Request object. However, when a new Request is instantiated from an existing Request with a FormData body, the browser generates a new boundary for the body content, but the Content-Type header still contains the old boundary from the original request.

This causes the server to fail parsing the multipart form data because the boundary in the Content-Type header does not match the boundary used in the actual request body.

Example:
```ts
const formData = new FormData();
formData.append('title', title);
formData.append('uploadFile[file]', new Blob([fileContent]));

return await api.post('endpoint', { body: formData }).json();
```

With an afterResponse hook like:
```js
afterResponse: [
  async (request, options, response) => {
    if (response.status === 401) {
      const token = await ky('https://example.com/token').text();
      request.headers.set('Authorization', `token ${token}`);
      return ky(request, options);
    }
  }
]
```

The call to ky(request, options) in the hook does not regenerate the Content-Type header, which creates a boundary mismatch between the header and the request content. The Content-Type header should be deleted when creating a new Request from an existing Request with a FormData or URLSearchParams body, so the browser can regenerate it with the correct boundary.

Note that there is existing code that handles this for the searchParams code path, but it does not cover the general case where the input to ky is a Request object with a FormData body and no searchParams are involved.
